canonical:
  title: 賀冬至牋
  author: 李崇仁
  language: lzh
  text: 氣吹律管一陽載回禮展宮庭四方稱賀凡爲動植孰不懽榮恭惟齊聖廣淵聦明睿智雲行雨施生成體天地之心日就月將精一傳帝王之學鼎當道長之旦益擁川至之休伏念猥以庸資幸叨優寄開閶闔而拜冕雖阻班行望蓬萊以書雲聊欣慶瑞
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 賀冬至牋
  author: 李崇仁
  language: lzh
  text: 氣吹律管。一陽載回。禮展宮庭。四方稱賀。凡爲動植。孰不懽榮。恭惟齊聖廣淵。聦明睿智。雲行雨施。生成體天地之心。日就月將。精一傳帝王之學。鼎當道長之旦。益擁川至之休。伏念猥以庸資。幸叨優寄。開閶闔而拜冕。雖阻班行。望蓬萊以書雲。聊欣慶瑞。
korean:
  title: 하 동지전
  author: 이숭인
  language: kor
  text: 율관(律管)에 기운을 넣어 부니 일양(一陽)이 돌아오고, 궁정에 예식을 거행하자 사방이 하례하오니, 동물이나 식물 어느 것인들 기뻐하고 환영하지 않겠나이까. 공손히 생각하옵건대, 제성(齊聖)ㆍ광연(廣淵)하시고 총명ㆍ예지(睿智)하시어 운행우시(雲行雨施)는 생성(生成)에 천지의 마음을 체(體)하시고, 일취월장(日就月將)으로 정일(精一)히 제왕(帝王)의 학(學)을 전하시니, 때마침 도(道)가 길어지는 아침을 당하여 더욱 냇물이 흘러 이르는 복을 끌어안으리이다. 엎드려 생각하옵건대, 외람되이 용렬한 자질(資質)로서 다행히 후하게 내려주신 직책을 맡았사오니 비록 천문(天門)에 들어가 용안(龍顔)을 배알(拜謁)하는 반차(班次)에는 참가하지 못하오나, 제궐(帝闕)을 바라보며 상운(祥雲)을 적어, 애오라지 경사로운 상서를 기뻐하옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0350_010_0470&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Missive Celebrating the Winter Solstice
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The vital breath fills the pitch-pipes, and the first yang returns.
    Ceremonies unfold in the palace courts, and all four quarters offer their felicitations.
    Whether creatures that move or plants that grow—what among them does not rejoice and flourish?

    I humbly reflect upon Your Majesty's sageness and boundless wisdom,
    Your brilliance and penetrating insight.
    As clouds drift and rain falls, you embody the generative heart of heaven and earth.
    With each passing day and waxing moon, you transmit with singular devotion the learning of ancient kings.
    Now the Way lengthens at dawn's threshold,
    And the blessings of flowing waters gather ever more abundantly.

    Yet I, a humble servant of meager talent, have undeservedly received your generous appointment.
    Though I cannot ascend to the Celestial Gate to behold the Dragon Countenance among the ranks of court,
    I gaze toward the Imperial Palace and record the auspicious clouds,
    Taking solace in celebrating these propitious omens.
  footnotes:
    - The 'pitch-pipes' (律管) refer to ancient Chinese instruments used to mark the seasons; the 'first yang' (一陽) symbolizes the winter solstice as the moment when the positive cosmic force begins to return.
    - The imagery of clouds drifting and rain falling evokes the sage ruler's influence flowing naturally through the world, in accordance with Daoist and Confucian political philosophy.
    - The poem employs the conventions of official court correspondence, blending praise for the ruler with self-deprecating language typical of the genre.
